# ============================================================
# SECOND GLANCE — .cursorrules
# AR Web App | Personal Project
# ============================================================

## PROJECT OVERVIEW

This is a marker-based WebAR web app called "Second Glance".
The concept: hand-drawn black and white stickers of mundane objects.
When a visitor points their phone camera at a sticker, an animated
scene plays on top of it, revealing the hidden life inside the object.

The app is built for an expo/exhibition setting.
Visitors use their own phone. No app download. No account.
One URL, open in browser, scan, experience.

---

## DESIGN BRIEF (for visual reference)

- Dark UI, minimal, immersive
- 4 screens: Landing, Loading, Active Scan, Error (camera denied)
- The design prototype was built in Claude Design
- All UI decisions should defer to that prototype unless explicitly told otherwise
- Mobile-first: design and test at 390x844px (iPhone 14 viewport)

---

## TECH STACK — DO NOT DEVIATE FROM THIS

- Language: Vanilla HTML, CSS, JavaScript only
- No frameworks (no React, Vue, Svelte, or any other)
- AR library: MindAR.js loaded via CDN
- Hosting: Vercel (static site, no server-side logic)
- No build tools, no npm, no bundlers
- No localStorage or sessionStorage
- No backend, no database, no API calls

MindAR.js CDN links (always use these exact versions):
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/mind-ar@1.2.5/dist/mindar-image.prod.js"></script>
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/mind-ar@1.2.5/dist/mindar-image-three.prod.js"></script>
  THREE.js (required by MindAR):
  <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/three@0.150.1/build/three.min.js"></script>

---

## PROJECT FILE STRUCTURE

Keep the project flat and simple:

  /second-glance-ar
  ├── index.html          ← entire app lives here to start
  ├── style.css           ← extracted only when index.html gets unwieldy
  ├── app.js              ← extracted only when index.html gets unwieldy
  ├── /targets
  │   ├── sticker-1.mind  ← MindAR compiled image target (sticker 1)
  │   └── sticker-2.mind  ← MindAR compiled image target (sticker 2)
  ├── /videos
  │   ├── scene-1.mp4     ← alpha video for sticker 1 (transparent background)
  │   └── scene-2.mp4     ← alpha video for sticker 2 (transparent background)
  └── /assets
      └── sticker-1.png   ← reference image of sticker (not used at runtime)
      └── sticker-2.png   ← reference image of sticker (not used at runtime)

---

## FOUR SCREENS — WHAT EACH DOES

### Screen 1: Landing
- Shown on first load
- Brief explanation of what to do ("Point your camera at a sticker")
- Single CTA button
- Tapping this button triggers camera permission request
- Do not auto-request camera on page load — browser requires a user gesture

### Screen 2: Loading
- Shown after user taps the CTA, while MindAR initialises
- Visual loading indicator (spinner or animated element)
- MindAR can take 2-5 seconds to initialise — this state must be visible

### Screen 3: Active Scan
- The fullscreen camera feed
- MindAR is active and scanning for sticker targets
- A subtle UI hint to tell the user where to point (frame or crosshair)
- When a sticker is detected: the corresponding alpha video plays on top of it
- When the sticker is lost: the video pauses or hides
- No other UI clutter — keep the experience immersive

### Screen 4: Error
- Shown if the user denies camera permission, or the browser does not support WebAR
- Clear, friendly message explaining what went wrong
- Instruction to try again or use a different browser
- Do not show a blank white screen under any circumstance

---

## CORE LOGIC — HOW MINAR WORKS

MindAR uses compiled .mind files as image targets.
Each .mind file is generated from a sticker illustration using the MindAR Image Target Compiler:
https://hiukim.github.io/mind-ar-js-doc/tools/compile

When a target is detected, MindAR fires an "targetFound" event.
When a target is lost, it fires a "targetLost" event.
Use these events to show/hide and play/pause the corresponding video.

Alpha videos must be WebM with alpha channel OR MP4 with a separate alpha mask.
Test alpha channel support per browser — Safari handles this differently than Chrome.

---

## WORKING METHOD — CRITICAL, FOLLOW THIS ALWAYS

This project is built step by step. Each step is tested before moving to the next.
Do NOT attempt to build the whole app at once.
Do NOT add features that haven't been asked for yet.
Do NOT refactor or restructure code unless explicitly asked.

### The build order is:

  PHASE 1 — Static shell (no AR yet)
    → Build all 4 screens in HTML/CSS only
    → Screen switching works via JS (show/hide divs)
    → No MindAR loaded yet
    → Test: all screens visible and switchable on mobile browser
    → STOP and wait for approval before Phase 2

  PHASE 2 — MindAR initialisation
    → Add MindAR CDN scripts
    → Load the .mind target file for sticker 1 only
    → Camera permission flow works
    → Loading screen shows during init, scan screen shows after
    → Test: camera opens, MindAR loads, no console errors
    → STOP and wait for approval before Phase 3

  PHASE 3 — First marker + video
    → Wire up targetFound / targetLost events for sticker 1
    → Alpha video for scene 1 plays on detection
    → Video pauses or hides on loss
    → Test: scan printed sticker 1, video appears, removing sticker pauses it
    → STOP and wait for approval before Phase 4

  PHASE 4 — Second marker + video
    → Add sticker 2 target and scene 2 video
    → Both stickers work independently
    → Test: both stickers detected correctly, no interference
    → STOP and wait for approval before Phase 5

  PHASE 5 — Polish and expo readiness
    → Error screen wired up for camera denial
    → UI refinements matching the Claude Design prototype
    → Test on both Android (Chrome) and iOS (Safari)
    → Deploy to Netlify, test via live URL on real devices

After Phase 5 is approved, the app is complete.

---

## CODING STYLE

- Write clean, readable, commented code
- Every logical block should have a short comment explaining what it does
- Prefer clarity over cleverness — this code will be presented and defended
- Use CSS custom properties (variables) for all colours and spacing
- All IDs and class names should be descriptive, not generic (use .scan-screen not .screen-3)
- Always handle the unhappy path (what if something fails or is missing?)

---

## WHEN IN DOUBT

- Ask before assuming
- Build less, test more
- One thing at a time
- If a step feels too large, split it into smaller steps and confirm before proceeding
